to hear the news from England,

1095
00:51:27,751 --> 00:51:31,320
but I do prophesy the election
rights on Fortinbras.

1096
00:51:31,322 --> 00:51:33,255
He has my dying voice.

1097
00:51:33,257 --> 00:51:36,692
So tell him
with the occurrents

1098
00:51:36,694 --> 00:51:40,195
that have solicited
more and less.

1099
00:51:40,197 --> 00:51:42,364
The rest...

1100
00:51:42,366 --> 00:51:44,232
Is silence.

1101
00:51:45,301 --> 00:51:48,303
[ Cheers and applause ]

1102
00:52:18,101 --> 00:52:20,302
[ Cheers and applause continue ]

1103
00:52:20,304 --> 00:52:21,803
Come!

1104
00:52:34,283 --> 00:52:37,252
In the words
of the immortal bard,

1105
00:52:37,254 --> 00:52:40,789
there will be
no more marriages!

1106
00:52:40,791 --> 00:52:43,358
[ Cheers and applause ]

1107
00:52:47,930 --> 00:52:50,198
[ Cheers and applause
intensify ]

1108
00:52:52,835 --> 00:52:54,836
[ Mid-tempo music playing ]

1109
00:52:54,838 --> 00:52:56,338
[ Indistinct conversations ]

1110
00:52:56,340 --> 00:52:57,839
Ifor.
Richard didn't tell me --

1111
00:52:57,841 --> 00:52:58,907
Will you accept
my apology?

1112
00:52:58,909 --> 00:53:01,176
For what?

1113
00:53:01,178 --> 00:53:03,779
I was wrong about you.

1114
00:53:03,781 --> 00:53:05,947
You've made him
very, very happy.

1115
00:53:05,949 --> 00:53:07,749
[ Laughs ]

1116
00:53:07,751 --> 00:53:09,685
Thank you.

1117
00:53:09,687 --> 00:53:13,221
Just...don't break his heart,
please.

1118
00:53:13,223 --> 00:53:15,757
Trust me -- he'll break <i>mine</i>
before I break <i>his.</i>

1119
00:53:19,228 --> 00:53:20,729
- Elizabeth.
- Yeah.

1120
00:53:20,731 --> 00:53:22,831
Elizabeth, you simply have to
meet this man.

1121
00:53:22,833 --> 00:53:23,932
This is
Ernest Lehman.

1122
00:53:23,934 --> 00:53:25,133
I'm a writer.

1123
00:53:25,135 --> 00:53:26,368
"Sweet Smell
of Success."

1124
00:53:26,370 --> 00:53:28,403
"North by Northwest" --
we love your work.

1125
00:53:28,405 --> 00:53:29,838
Well, thank you.

1126
00:53:29,840 --> 00:53:31,273
I wish you'd write
something for <i>me.</i>

1127
00:53:31,275 --> 00:53:33,108
Actually,
I have something --

1128
00:53:33,110 --> 00:53:35,177
"Who's Afraid
of Virginia Woolf?"

1129
00:53:35,179 --> 00:53:36,311
Oh, I love the play!

1130
00:53:36,313 --> 00:53:38,113
But we could do it
<i>together.</i>

1131
00:53:38,115 --> 00:53:39,848
Well,
you start a new film --

1132
00:53:39,850 --> 00:53:41,983
"The Spy Who Came in From The Cold."

1133
00:53:41,985 --> 00:53:44,286
Yes, but I could do this one
after that.

1134
00:53:44,288 --> 00:53:46,855
I'm afraid you're a little
too masculine for George,

1135
00:53:46,857 --> 00:53:48,724
and I can't quite see it.

1136
00:53:48,726 --> 00:53:51,226
And I can't imagine the two
of you fighting like that.

1137
00:53:51,228 --> 00:53:54,396
Oh. Well, do you hear that,
my little sugar tart?

1138
00:53:54,398 --> 00:53:56,031
He can't imagine
us fighting.

1139
00:53:56,033 --> 00:53:58,266
Well, it doesn't matter,
because why would anyone hire

1140
00:53:58,268 --> 00:54:00,035
a vomiting vat of vodka
like yourself?

1141
00:54:00,037 --> 00:54:02,404
Well, at least when I vomit,
I make mellifluous sounds,

1142
00:54:02,406 --> 00:54:04,306
unlike your little
mouse-crap squeaks.

1143
00:54:04,308 --> 00:54:05,507
- Oh, mellifluous?
- Yes.

1144
00:54:05,509 --> 00:54:07,342
Mellifluous?

1145
00:54:07,344 --> 00:54:08,910
What was he -- some Roman
homosexual that you buggered?

1146
00:54:08,912 --> 00:54:10,078
[ Laughs ]

1147
00:54:11,280 --> 00:54:12,347
Mellifluous,
bring me my wine.

1148
00:54:12,349 --> 00:54:14,316
That's wonderful,
darling.

1149
00:54:14,318 --> 00:54:17,886
See, you have to understand --
we <i>enjoy</i> fighting.

1150
00:54:17,888 --> 00:54:19,254
[ Laughs ]

1151
00:54:19,256 --> 00:54:21,289
We really do.
We're masters of the art.

1152
00:54:21,291 --> 00:54:23,925
I guess we could wait
until after Richard's film.

1153
00:54:26,795 --> 00:54:29,097
...Laurence Olivier
for "Othello,"

1154
00:54:29,599 --> 00:54:32,334
Rod Steiger
for "The Pawnbroker,"

1155
00:54:32,336 --> 00:54:33,769
and Richard Burton

1156
00:54:33,771 --> 00:54:36,304
for "The Spy
Who Came in From The Cold."

1157
00:54:36,306 --> 00:54:37,839
