what you're <i>going</i> to lose.

1300
01:00:43,673 --> 01:00:44,672
Her.

1301
01:00:46,242 --> 01:00:47,675
I was wrong, you know.

1302
01:00:47,677 --> 01:00:51,146
I thought
you were too good for her,

1303
01:00:51,148 --> 01:00:54,282
but she's too good
for <i>you.</i>

1304
01:00:54,284 --> 01:00:56,451
She's just won
a bloody Oscar,

1305
01:00:56,453 --> 01:01:00,188
and you can't enjoy it with her
because you're moping.

1306
01:01:00,190 --> 01:01:05,193
Can't you see I'm afraid
I'm not enough for her?

1307
01:01:07,630 --> 01:01:09,731
[ Seagulls squawking ]

1308
01:01:13,702 --> 01:01:15,203
"Enseamed"?

1309
01:01:15,205 --> 01:01:16,871
That's not a word.

1310
01:01:18,307 --> 01:01:19,807
Richard --
just the man we need.

1311
01:01:19,809 --> 01:01:22,210
Will you tell them
that "enseamed" is a word?

1312
01:01:22,212 --> 01:01:24,312
Elizabeth is right.
"Enseamed" <i>is</i> a word.

1313
01:01:24,314 --> 01:01:27,715
It means, um...
"Greasy."

1314
01:01:27,717 --> 01:01:29,317
Good morning, Bernard.

1315
01:01:29,319 --> 01:01:31,786
What brings our esteemed
business manager to Mexico?

1316
01:01:31,788 --> 01:01:33,588
Good news, hmm?

1317
01:01:33,590 --> 01:01:36,291
Why don't you guys
go in for a swim?

1318
01:01:36,293 --> 01:01:37,458
Off you go.

1319
01:01:39,328 --> 01:01:40,595
So?

1320
01:01:40,597 --> 01:01:42,330
I have, uh,
prepared some statements.

1321
01:01:42,332 --> 01:01:43,798
Yeah, well,
skip the paperwork.

1322
01:01:43,800 --> 01:01:45,800
Out with it, man.
Give it to me straight.

1323
01:01:45,802 --> 01:01:47,936
Don't be mean to Bernard.
He works hard for us.

1324
01:01:47,938 --> 01:01:49,871
I don't dispute it.

1325
01:01:49,873 --> 01:01:51,773
It's just that when it <i>is</i>
good news, he sends a telegram,

1326
01:01:51,775 --> 01:01:53,875
and when it's bad news,
he slinks in like an undertaker.

1327
01:01:53,877 --> 01:01:56,811
Bernard, ignore him.
Tell me.

1328
01:01:56,813 --> 01:01:59,214
Since Richard
wants it straight...

1329
01:01:59,216 --> 01:02:00,815
You're broke.

1330
01:02:00,817 --> 01:02:02,650
Oh, and here I was thinking
it was something serious.

1331
01:02:02,652 --> 01:02:05,286
How can we be broke?
How is that possible?

1332
01:02:05,288 --> 01:02:07,255
That's...Everything.

1333
01:02:08,624 --> 01:02:11,726
But if Richard takes
"The Comedians"...

1334
01:02:11,728 --> 01:02:14,262
"The Comedians"?
When were you offered that role?

1335
01:02:14,264 --> 01:02:15,630
I'm turning it down.

1336
01:02:15,632 --> 01:02:17,765
Richard, they offered you
3/4 of a million.

1337
01:02:17,767 --> 01:02:18,766
But it's with Sophia.

1338
01:02:18,768 --> 01:02:20,235
[ Chuckling ] Oh.

1339
01:02:20,237 --> 01:02:21,769
Screw Sophia.
<i>I</i> will do it.

1340
01:02:21,771 --> 01:02:23,871
Already asked.
They can't afford you.

1341
01:02:23,873 --> 01:02:25,707
Well,
I'll cut my fee in half.

1342
01:02:25,709 --> 01:02:27,976
Tell them I'll do it
for half a million.

1343
01:02:27,978 --> 01:02:29,244
Will we be all right
<i>then?</i>

1344
01:02:29,246 --> 01:02:30,678
For a while.

1345
01:02:30,680 --> 01:02:34,682
But after taxes, hotels,
uh, travel, staff...

1346
01:02:34,684 --> 01:02:36,918
And we need more staff
for security.

1347
01:02:36,920 --> 01:02:38,886
The paparazzi
have found us.

1348
01:02:38,888 --> 01:02:40,488
More staff?

1349
01:02:40,490 --> 01:02:42,523
Now, if you were
any kind of a manager, Bernard,

1350
01:02:42,525 --> 01:02:43,758
you'd be able
to find us somewhere

1351
01:02:43,760 --> 01:02:45,393
where we'd never
had to pay any taxes

1352
01:02:45,395 --> 01:02:47,829
and where the damn photographers
would never find us.

1353
01:02:47,831 --> 01:02:49,464
Now you're asking
the impossible.

1354
01:02:49,466 --> 01:02:51,466
The only place you two
will get any peace and quiet

1355
01:02:51,468 --> 01:02:52,967
is in the middle
of the bloody ocean.

1356
01:02:54,837 --> 01:02:56,304
Bernard,
you are a genius.

1357
01:03:00,476 --> 01:03:02,477
Richard: Okay,
now you can open your eyes.

1358
01:03:02,479 --> 01:03:04,812
[ All gasp ]

1359
01:03:04,814 --> 01:03:06,414
Our new home.

1360
01:03:06,416 --> 01:03:08,283
[ Laughter ]

1361
01:03:08,285 --> 01:03:10,285
Well, come on.
All aboard, all aboard.

1362
01:03:10,287 --> 01:03:12,020
Make yourselves at home.
Don't drown.

1363
01:03:14,290 --> 01:03:16,591
A boat --
live on a boat.

1364
01:03:16,593 --> 01:03:18,693
A yacht, mother.
There <i>is</i> a difference.

1365
01:03:18,695 --> 01:03:22,363
Yes,
it's much more expensive.

1366
01:03:23,032 --> 01:03:24,799
[ Laughs ]

1367
01:03:24,801 --> 01:03:25,967
[ Laughter ]

1368
01:03:25,969 --> 01:03:28,002
[ Indistinct talking ]

1369
01:03:28,004 --> 01:03:29,037
[ Both laugh ]

1370
01:03:30,839 --> 01:03:32,006
Who's that?

1371
01:03:32,008 --> 01:03:33,708
My photographer.

1372
01:03:39,415 --> 01:03:43,484
[ Seagulls squawking ]

1373
01:03:43,486 --> 01:03:45,053
Damn and blast it.

1374
01:03:45,055 --> 01:03:46,988
I thought we got a yacht
to get <i>away</i> from the press.

1375
01:03:46,990 --> 01:03:49,357
But he's not press.
He's my photographer.

1376
01:03:49,359 --> 01:03:50,725
"My photographer"?

1377
01:03:50,727 --> 01:03:53,861
What are you --
potentate, royalty?

1378
01:03:53,863 --> 01:03:55,830
There have probably been
more photographs taken of you

1379
01:03:55,832 --> 01:03:56,964
than anyone else
on earth.

1380
01:03:56,966 --> 01:03:58,333
Why would you
want more?

1381
01:03:58,335 --> 01:03:59,567
Because
his are beautiful.

1382
01:03:59,569 --> 01:04:01,836
No.
<i>You</i> are beautiful.

1383
01:04:01,838 --> 01:04:03,471
He just knows
how to point a camera.

1384
01:04:03,473 --> 01:04:04,572
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

1385
01:04:04,574 --> 01:04:06,374
Will you stop that?!

1386
01:04:06,376 --> 01:04:07,809
He doesn't speak English,
Richard.

1387
01:04:07,811 --> 01:04:09,477
Trust me --
he understood <i>that.</i>

1388
01:04:09,479 --> 01:04:10,845
Are you jealous?

1389
01:04:10,847 --> 01:04:11,979
Why? Should I be?

1390
01:04:11,981 --> 01:04:13,348
No, of course not.

1391
01:04:13,350 --> 01:04:15,016
Because if you so much
as stroke his hand,

1392
01:04:15,018 --> 01:04:16,084
I'll never speak to you
again.

1393
01:04:16,086 --> 01:04:17,352
Same goes for you.

1394
01:04:18,020 --> 01:04:19,053
Bit young for you,
isn't he?

1395
01:04:19,055 --> 01:04:20,421
Stop it.

1396
01:04:20,423 --> 01:04:21,489
Skinny, too.
You'd all but flatten him.

1397
01:04:21,491 --> 01:04:22,890
Ooh, I'd be careful,
Richard.

1398
01:04:22,892 --> 01:04:25,059
<i>You</i> could stand
to lose a few pounds.

1399
01:04:25,061 --> 01:04:27,695
Yes, but at least mine doesn't all
pool in my fingers, Miss pudgy digits.

1400
01:04:29,031 --> 01:04:29,964
What?

1401
01:04:33,902 --> 01:04:34,936
What?!

1402
01:04:37,072 --> 01:04:40,108
Boopsy.

1403
01:04:40,110 --> 01:04:43,978
Boopsy,
Richard wants to play.

1404
01:04:43,980 --> 01:04:45,380
[ Sighs ]

1405
01:04:45,382 --> 01:04:46,914
Oh, don't cry.

1406
01:04:46,916 --> 01:04:48,015
I'm not crying!

1407
01:04:48,017 --> 01:04:49,884
I'm trying not to stick you
with a knife

1408
01:04:49,886 --> 01:04:51,619
in your fat,
blubbery stomach.

1409
01:04:51,621 --> 01:04:52,887
Well, knife away!
Throw me overboard!

1410
01:04:52,889 --> 01:04:54,922
Now you can feel
my pudgy hands now!

1411
01:04:54,924 --> 01:04:57,058
Hey, these are not
pudgy hands!

1412
01:04:57,060 --> 01:04:58,626
They are fat,
and they're pudgy!

1413
01:04:58,628 --> 01:05:01,028
I love these hands.

1414
01:05:01,030 --> 01:05:02,063
Are you sure?

1415
01:05:02,065 --> 01:05:03,865
1,000%.

1416
01:05:03,867 --> 01:05:06,401
Do you want
to make them beautiful?

1417
01:05:06,403 --> 01:05:07,635
But they <i>are...</i>

1418
01:05:07,637 --> 01:05:09,070
Beautiful.

1419
01:05:09,072 --> 01:05:12,774
Do you want to make them
<i>more</i> beautiful?

1420
01:05:15,411 --> 01:05:17,412
I need a ring.

1421
01:05:17,414 --> 01:05:19,147
A <i>big</i> ring.

1422
01:05:23,014 --> 01:05:26,147
Auctioneer:
$700,000 raise Mr. Onassis.

1423
01:05:26,422 --> 01:05:29,157
Auctioneer:
I have $750,000 on the phone.

1424
01:05:30,726 --> 01:05:32,193
I now have $800,000
with Mr. Onassis.

1425
01:05:32,195 --> 01:05:33,528
$850,000.

1426
01:05:33,530 --> 01:05:36,998
$850,000 on the phone.

1427
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:38,132
$900,000.

1428
01:05:38,134 --> 01:05:39,567
$950,000.

1429
01:05:39,569 --> 01:05:41,769
$950,000 on the phone.

1430
01:05:42,671 --> 01:05:43,971
Yes.

1431
01:05:43,973 --> 01:05:46,174
Now $1 million
with Cartier, Paris.

1432
01:05:46,176 --> 01:05:47,542
And 50.

1433
01:05:47,544 --> 01:05:51,212
I have $1,050,000
on the phone.

1434
01:05:51,214 --> 01:05:56,517
The bid stands at $1,050,000
on the phone.

1435
01:05:56,519 --> 01:05:57,552
[ Gavel bangs ]

1436
01:05:57,554 --> 01:05:58,786
Sold to...

1437
01:06:00,222 --> 01:06:03,024
...Mr. Richard Burton.

1438
01:06:10,599 --> 01:06:13,067
[ Indistinct talking ]

1439
01:06:26,215 --> 01:06:27,748
[ All gasp, murmur ]

1440
01:06:27,750 --> 01:06:30,251
Woman:
Oh...My...Goodness.

1441
01:06:30,253 --> 01:06:32,487
Now, <i>that</i> is a ring.

1442
01:06:32,489 --> 01:06:34,789
Richard here told me
that my hands looked fat,

1443
01:06:34,791 --> 01:06:36,991
so, of course,
I made him buy me something

1444
01:06:36,993 --> 01:06:39,193
that would make them
look small.

1445
01:06:39,195 --> 01:06:41,062
[ Laughter ]

1446
01:06:41,064 --> 01:06:42,530
Come on.
We must get a drink in you.

1447
01:06:42,532 --> 01:06:44,165
[ Sighs ]
Here you are.

1448
01:06:44,167 --> 01:06:46,133
Don't worry. It's not like this
around here all the time.

1449
01:06:46,135 --> 01:06:48,769
Normally, it's just, uh,
us and the children,

1450
01:06:48,771 --> 01:06:50,671
well, nannies and the crew,
and there's --

1451
01:06:50,673 --> 01:06:52,540
there's a couple of cooks.
[ Laughs ]

1452
01:06:52,542 --> 01:06:54,175
And, of course,
my brother, Ifor,

1453
01:06:54,177 --> 01:06:56,143
and Bernard,
our business manager.

1454
01:06:56,145 --> 01:06:57,278
Come here, Bernard.

1455
01:06:57,280 --> 01:06:58,946
I'm trying
to explain to Bernard

1456
01:06:58,948 --> 01:07:00,781
that since
this whole yacht costs

1457
01:07:00,783 --> 01:07:02,750
only -- what --
$30,000 a year to run,

1458
01:07:02,752 --> 01:07:06,621
think of all the money we save
on hotels and houses.

1459
01:07:06,623 --> 01:07:08,122
Plus, there's no taxes,
you see.

1460
01:07:08,124 --> 01:07:09,690
Don't tell anybody,
but we --

1461
01:07:09,692 --> 01:07:11,826
we can take the dogs
anywhere we want.

1462
01:07:11,828 --> 01:07:14,128
Can't we?
We just leave them on the boat.

1463
01:07:20,302 --> 01:07:21,802
[ Sighs ]

1464
01:07:23,205 --> 01:07:25,273
Two Bloody Marys.
Thank you, Jacques.

1465
01:07:28,577 --> 01:07:30,111
[ Coughs ]

1466
01:07:30,113 --> 01:07:32,146
I've ordered breakfast.

1467
01:07:32,148 --> 01:07:33,314
[ Groans ]

1468
01:07:33,316 --> 01:07:35,249
[ Sighs ]

1469
01:07:35,251 --> 01:07:37,585
Do you know
it's December?

1470
01:07:37,587 --> 01:07:39,253
You're joking.

1471
01:07:39,255 --> 01:07:41,188
The children have been
complaining

1472
01:07:41,190 --> 01:07:42,857
it's not
at all christmasy.

1473
01:07:42,859 --> 01:07:46,327
The <i>children</i>
are complaining?

1474
01:07:47,663 --> 01:07:49,764
Well, we'd all
like to be in the snow.

1475
01:07:51,199 --> 01:07:53,167
I supposed we could open up
the house in Switzerland.

1476
01:07:57,739 --> 01:08:00,708
[ Sighs ]

1477
01:08:00,710 --> 01:08:03,110
Mr. Burton.
I have not seen you in...

1478
01:08:03,112 --> 01:08:05,079
- Almost two years, I think
-  Yeah.

1479
01:08:05,081 --> 01:08:07,048
Are you back?
Miss Taylor?

1480
01:08:07,050 --> 01:08:08,783
Elizabeth and the children
arrive tomorrow.

1481
01:08:08,785 --> 01:08:10,017
We are
the advance guard

1482
01:08:10,019 --> 01:08:11,185
come to open the house
for Christmas.

1483
01:08:11,187 --> 01:08:12,620
Bloody weather
you're having.

1484
01:08:12,622 --> 01:08:15,189
Tomorrow
will be beautiful.

1485
01:08:15,191 --> 01:08:16,958
Some wine to start?

1486
01:08:18,760 --> 01:08:20,761
Richard:
Ah, good old Bernard,

1487
01:08:20,763 --> 01:08:24,732
calculating exactly
what Christmas will cost.

1488
01:08:24,734 --> 01:08:27,301
Don't look at <i>me.</i>
Talk to Elizabeth.

1489
01:08:27,303 --> 01:08:28,936
You're as bad
as each other.

1490
01:08:28,938 --> 01:08:33,174
I've never seen two people
piss it away so bloody quickly.

1491
01:08:33,176 --> 01:08:37,311
Oh, that's good, coming from one
of the dozens of family members on salary.

1492
01:08:37,313 --> 01:08:38,779
I <i>work</i> for my money.

1493
01:08:38,781 --> 01:08:40,848
As, dear brother, do I.

1494
01:08:45,120 --> 01:08:46,320
Oh, no.
Don't you get up.

1495
01:08:46,322 --> 01:08:48,189
You finish up here.

1496
01:08:48,191 --> 01:08:51,125
I'll go open up your house,
and then I'll come back for you!

1497
01:08:51,127 --> 01:08:52,159
Very well, good man.

1498
01:08:52,161 --> 01:08:55,229
You can always count
on Ifor.

1499
01:09:03,372 --> 01:09:05,306
[ Sighs ]

1500
01:09:05,308 --> 01:09:07,808
[ Keys clatter ]

1501
01:09:07,810 --> 01:09:11,312
[ Switch clicking ]

1502
01:09:11,314 --> 01:09:13,214
[ Sighs ]

1503
01:09:24,693 --> 01:09:27,228
[ Clattering ]

1504
01:09:27,230 --> 01:09:29,664
[ Grunts, moans ]

1505
01:09:30,966 --> 01:09:33,401
[ Woman speaking French
over P.A. ]

1506
01:09:38,173 --> 01:09:40,274
[ Telephone ringing ]

1507
01:09:44,846 --> 01:09:46,847
I'm...very sorry.

1508
01:09:46,849 --> 01:09:48,716
[ Gasps ]

1509
01:09:48,718 --> 01:09:51,385
It's his spine.

1510
01:09:51,387 --> 01:09:53,387
He'll never walk again.

1511
01:10:15,977 --> 01:10:17,845
[ Laughter ]

1512
01:10:17,847 --> 01:10:20,748
[ Funk music playing ]

1513
01:10:23,852 --> 01:10:25,820
Can you please
shut that thing off?!

1514
01:10:25,822 --> 01:10:27,888
[ Music continues ]

1515
01:10:27,890 --> 01:10:29,023
[ Laughter ]

1516
01:10:39,968 --> 01:10:44,338
Can I please
get some peace and quiet?!

1517
01:10:44,340 --> 01:10:47,742
[ Volume decreases ]

1518
01:10:47,744 --> 01:10:49,510
[ Splash, music stops ]

1519
01:10:51,046 --> 01:10:52,012
[ Door slams ]

1520
01:10:52,014 --> 01:10:53,314
What is your problem?

1521
01:10:53,316 --> 01:10:54,949
Nothing.
Now I drowned it.

1522
01:10:54,951 --> 01:10:56,450
Our guests
are trying to have fun.

1523
01:10:56,452 --> 01:10:58,285
Yes, and so was I --
until you ruined it!

1524
01:10:58,287 --> 01:10:59,520
Oh, Richard,
I'll ruin it.

1525
01:10:59,522 --> 01:11:00,521
Ah!
That's my next job.

1526
01:11:00,523 --> 01:11:02,456
"Bluebeard"?

1527
01:11:02,458 --> 01:11:06,127
"Bluebeard" -- utter claptrap,
but for the money, I will dance.

1528
01:11:06,129 --> 01:11:07,928
You know, he murdered
several of his wives.

1529
01:11:07,930 --> 01:11:09,330
I'm beginning
to identify with him.

1530
01:11:09,332 --> 01:11:11,799
And who plays these wives?
Hmm?

1531
01:11:11,801 --> 01:11:14,468
Let me guess --
they're all 12 years old.

1532
01:11:14,470 --> 01:11:16,070
No.

1533
01:11:16,072 --> 01:11:19,473
They've only cast Raquel Welch
and Virna Lisi so far.

1534
01:11:19,475 --> 01:11:21,942
Oh, so you're gonna do
this piece of crap

1535
01:11:21,944 --> 01:11:23,344
and then
grope all these girls.

1536
01:11:23,346 --> 01:11:24,779
This is a job.

1537
01:11:24,781 --> 01:11:28,282
What do you think
pays for all of this?!

1538
01:11:28,284 --> 01:11:29,950
Witch, that's a book!

1539
01:11:29,952 --> 01:11:31,452
Oh! Witch?!

1540
01:11:31,454 --> 01:11:32,486
Yes!

1541
01:11:32,488 --> 01:11:34,221
Yes!

1542
01:11:34,223 --> 01:11:36,056
You put a spell on me,
didn't you?!

1543
01:11:36,058 --> 01:11:38,259
I should've stayed on the stage,
like Scofield,

1544
01:11:38,261 --> 01:11:40,327
instead of
wasting my talent on you!

1545
01:11:40,329 --> 01:11:41,362
- Oh, on me?!
- Yes!

1546
01:11:41,364 --> 01:11:42,563
- On me?!
- On you!

1547
01:11:42,565 --> 01:11:44,465
I love it
when you get angry, Richard!

1548
01:11:44,467 --> 01:11:45,866
Oh, really?

1549
01:11:45,868 --> 01:11:47,368
This is what Richard Jenkins
would've wanted.

1550
01:11:47,370 --> 01:11:49,303
You know, there's only one way
